<li id="fn4" role="doc-endnote"><p><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mahatma_Gandhi">Mohandas Karamchand Gandhi</a> (1869-1948) needs no introduction. As far as the Hindi-Urdu debates go, he can be placed fairly solidly in “Camp Hindustani” as described in the historical background above: he encouraged the use of the term “Hindustani” to refer to the language as it was spoken by laypeople, and wanted both orthographies to be accepted ways of writing the language.<a href="#fnref4" class="footnote-back" role="doc-backlink">↩︎</a></p></li>
<li id="fn5" role="doc-endnote"><p>“Camp Hindi” used the phrase “the Right of Hindi” (हिंदी का हक · <span dir="rtl">ہندی کا حق</span>, or sometimes the Sanskritized variant हिंदी का अधिकार · <span dir="rtl">ہندی کا ادھکار</span>) frequently during the Hindi-Urdu debates, the idea being that their Sanskritized vision of “Hindi” had a <em>right</em> to be the national language of India, and that Hindus had to demand this right. It continues to be used occasionally today (for instance, in demands that Hindi be recognized as an <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Official_languages_of_the_United_Nations">Official Language of the United Nations</a>, or in deploring the usage of English or Hinglish by the Indian media). I do not have access to enough data to pinpoint the precise origins of the phrase.<a href="#fnref5" class="footnote-back" role="doc-backlink">↩︎</a></p></li>
<li id="fn6" role="doc-endnote"><p><em><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Munshi">Munshi</a></em> is a title used for scholars, scribes, or translators.<a href="#fnref6" class="footnote-back" role="doc-backlink">↩︎</a></p></li>
<li id="fn7" role="doc-endnote"><p><em><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sahib">Sahab</a></em> is a title used broadly to convey respect.<a href="#fnref7" class="footnote-back" role="doc-backlink">↩︎</a></p></li>
<li id="fn8" role="doc-endnote"><p><em><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mirza">Mirza</a></em> is a title used for royal princes, high noblemen, military commanders, or scholars.<a href="#fnref8" class="footnote-back" role="doc-backlink">↩︎</a></p></li>
<li id="fn9" role="doc-endnote"><p>Hindustani has three second person pronouns which differ in the formality they convey (i.e., it has a three-way <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/T%E2%80%93V_distinction">T-V distinction</a>). The dialogue begins with both participants speaking at the highest level of formality. At this point, Mirza Mohammad Iqbal drops down to the middle level of formality. This lapse in social decorum is perhaps indicative of Iqbal’s building irritation.<a href="#fnref9" class="footnote-back" role="doc-backlink">↩︎</a></p></li>
<li id="fn10" role="doc-endnote"><p>At this point, Munshi Narayan Prashad also lapses to the middle level of formality.<a href="#fnref10" class="footnote-back" role="doc-backlink">↩︎</a></p></li>
<li id="fn11" role="doc-endnote"><p>Here Mirza Mohammad Iqbal switches back to using the most formal second person pronouns. He maintains this distance for the remainder of the dialogue.<a href="#fnref11" class="footnote-back" role="doc-backlink">↩︎</a></p></li>
<li id="fn12" role="doc-endnote"><p>Here Munshi Narayan Prashad also switches back to using the most formal second person pronouns. He also maintains this distance for the remainder of the dialogue.<a href="#fnref12" class="footnote-back" role="doc-backlink">↩︎</a></p></li>
<li id="fn13" role="doc-endnote"><p>The reference is to <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/South_Asian_pickles">South Asian pickles</a>: fruits and vegetables pickled in oil or brine with a lot of spices. They are usually spicy, sour, and very fragrant. I am not aware of health concerns associated to these pickles, but maybe rumors of such concerns were prevalent at the time of this writing.<a href="#fnref13" class="footnote-back" role="doc-backlink">↩︎</a></p></li>
